Tameside MBC wish to procure suppliers for a Framework to provide adaptations to Residential Properties(owner occupiers, private tenants and social tenants who live in properties within the Metropolitan Borough of Tameside). Suppliers are required for the delivery of construction related works to properties requiring adaptation changes to assist occupants to maintain a degree of independence when disability limits daily activity.
This Framework will have 3 Lots comprising of the following:
LOT 1 major internal & external adaptations to the property where the cost is more than £1000 funded by DFG but cannot be more than £30,000 (this Lot will not include extensions to properties which will be subject to an independent procurement exercise);
LOT 2 Minor external and internal works to properties with an individual value less than £1000;
LOT 3 Minor external an internal works relating to electrical and Visual Impairment works with an individual value of less than £1000. Expressions of interest and all documents are available on the Northwest procurement Portal https://www.the-chest.org.uk/

Tameside Council is the Lead commissioner for provision of Public Analyst Services and related emergency call out services for the Greater Manchester Public Protection Partnership. The Service will support Local Authority Departments and Greater Manchester Combined Authority to respond to respond to hazardous and environmental protection incidents in the Greater Manchester area with a 24 hour, 365 days a year contactable and reactive service The Emergency Call Out service is to provide support to Partner Authorities to respond to incidents and will provide the following:
A 24 hour, 365 days a year contactable and reactive service
Provision of immediate over-the-phone advice
Prompt on-site attendance anywhere within the Greater Manchester conurbation (within a period of 90 minutes for 95% of call outs). Advice and attendance requirements will generally relate to hazardous materials incidents.
On-site analytical capability for identification of gas, liquids, powders and solids;
Ability to provide advice in dealing with environmental incidents, including the release, spillage, emission or leachate of bio/chemical agents potentially harmful to health;
Ability to work in conjunction with Local Authority, Emergency Service and / or Health Sector personnel;
Knowledge and ability to assist in the event of a terrorist Chemical, Biological, Radiological or Nuclear (CBRNe)type event;
Participation in a small number of training events and / or exercises each year. Response including a mobile laboratory including fume cupboard, Personal Protective Equipment, chemical testing, chemical databases (for example Chemdata, Hazard Manager or other equivalent systems), IT resources, sampling equipment.
scientific responder(s) to attend calls on request to conduct on site analysis and provide appropriate scientific advice.
an advice and response capability 24 hours per day 365 days per year, including: -
Provision of immediate telephone advice (within 10 minutes of a request) by a suitably experienced and qualified person.
Provision of prompt on-site attendance of mobile laboratory and suitably qualified and experienced person at incidents anywhere within the Greater Manchester Conurbation

Public Analyst Services for the Greater Manchester Public Protection Partnership. The Service supports Local Authority Trading Standards and Environmental Health Departments to enforce the provisions of the Food Safety Act 1990, Agriculture Act, Consumer Protection Act 1987 and supplementary Regulations including air quality, contaminated land and water sampling.The services required include the testing and analysis of goods and samples submitted by the Partner Authorities. The type of materials to be tested will include the following non-exclusive list:
 Food products for composition and presence of foreign bodies/material;
Animal feed samples;The safety of consumer products;
 The safety of drinking water;
 Chemical and investigative analysis of polluted water; soils, vegetation and other materials;
 Bulk asbestos and asbestos in air sampling;
Nitrogen Dioxide (NO2 ) tubes and other gases/particulate matter;
 Heavy metals and other compounds in air;
Low level Gamma radiation in foods and vegetation;
 Lead content of motor vehicle fuels;
 Toy safety
 Fire safety to BS476
 Any other sample consistent with the work of the Public Analyst.
The Provider is expected to supply the full range of tests required by the Partner Authorities in executing their enforcement duties as part of their official controls. Where the Provider cannot provide these directly, or it is more cost effective and efficient to subcontract, the provider is expected to enter into and manage subcontracting arrangements to ensure that all required tests can be performed in a timely manner to the required standard
Analysis of formal and informal (official) samples must be under the direction of a Public Analyst to fully comply with the requirements of the Food Safety Act. The Provider will be responsible for the provision of Public Analysts who will be appointed by the Partner Authorities to perform this role on their behalf.
All test performed will be under the supervision of suitably qualified staff.
All laboratories used must comply with relevant legislation and industry standards
